    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1928-06-05T03:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1928-06-05T03:00:00-05:00" n="173"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d173">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/10033: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">MacMurray</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1928-06-05T16:00:00+08:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">June 5, 1928—4 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received June 5—10:40 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>426. 1. Upon the departure last night of Chang Hsueh-liang,<note n="68"
                        xml:id="d173fn68">Son of Chang Tso-lin, and commander of Fengtien Third
                        Army, under the Peking Government.</note> Yang Yu-ting<note n="69"
                        xml:id="d173fn69">Chief of Staff in Chang Tso-lin’s forces.</note> and the
                    principal remaining officials connected with the Fengtien regime, the control of
                    Peking is in the hands of the committee of elder statesmen headed by Wang
                        Shih-tseng,<note n="70" xml:id="d173fn70">Refers apparently to Gen. Wang
                        Chih-chen, chairman of the Committee of Safety.</note> mentioned <pb
                        facs="0354" n="236" xml:id="pg_236"/> in paragraph 4 of my number 409, May
                    31, 10 p.m. [<hi rend="italic">a.m.</hi>].<note n="71" xml:id="d173fn71">Not
                        printed.</note> One reliable Fengtien brigade of about five thousand men
                    remains to preserve order in the city. Plans are under negotiation for the
                    peaceful withdrawal of this force upon the arrival of the incoming Nationalist
                    troops. Forces of Yen<note n="72" xml:id="d173fn72">Marshal Yen Hsi-shan.</note>
                    and Feng<note n="73" xml:id="d173fn73">Marshal Feng Yu-hsiang.</note> are
                    reported within day’s march of city and question of which will first arrive is
                    purely speculative.</p>
                <p>2. All Manchurian troops are clearing this area without disorder. Heavy troop
                    traffic has prevented operation of passenger trains between here and Tientsin
                    since June 3rd. Both Tientsin and Peking remain quiet and there are apparent[ly]
                    no signs of agitation.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">MacMurray</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
